"en":{"about 1170–1230":"about 1170–1230","1170–1230":"1170–1230","1170–1244":"1170–1244","1190–1241":"1190–1241","1192–1267":"1192–1267","1218–Male":"1218–Deceased","1170–1202":"1170–1202","1140–1202":"1140–1202","1190":"1190","about 1170":"about 1170","1230":"1230","1241":"1241","1140":"1140","1192":"1192","Dec 1202":"December 1202","Abt 1218":"about 1218","1170":"1170","1202":"1202","1267":"1267","1244":"1244","1218":"1218","Oxford, Oxfordshire, England":"Oxford, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Coggeshall, Oxfordshire, England":"Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Coggs, Witney, Oxfordshire, England":"Witney, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Oxfordshire, England":"Oxfordshire, England","England":"England, United Kingdom","Cogges, Oxfordshire, England":"Cogges, Oxfordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Arsic","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Slovenian (<b>Uršič</b>) and Croatian (<b>Uršić</b>): metronymic from the female personal name <i>Urša</i>, a short form of <i>Uršula</i> (from Latin <i>Ursula</i>, a diminutive of <i>ursa</i> ‘she-bear’; see   Urschel  ), or, as a Slovenian surname only, a patronymic from the male personal name <i>Urh</i> (see   Urch  ).","Croatian (<b>Ursić</b>): patronymic from the old male personal name <i>Urso</i> of Italian origin (ultimately from Latin <i>ursus</i> ‘bear’), or a metronymic from the female personal name <i>Ursa</i>, a short form of <i>Ursula</i> (see above)."],"variants":[{"name":"Ursich","meanings":["Americanized or Italianized form of Slovenian <b>Uršič</b> or Croatian <b>Uršić</b> and <b>Ursić</b> (see   Ursic  )."]},{"name":"Urschel","meanings":["German: from a vernacular pet form of the female personal name <i>Ursula</i> (from a diminutive of Latin <i>ursa</i> ‘she-bear’). Saint Ursula was a 4th-century Christian martyr who was put to death at Cologne."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Arsic was born about 1170, his father, Alexander Arsic, was 2 and his mother, Emma de Solenbi, was 31. He married Sybil de Crevecoeur in Oxford, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 2 daughters. He died in 1230, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 61."},"et":{"about 1170–1230":"umbes 1170–1230","1170–1230":"1170–1230","1170–1244":"1170–1244","1190–1241":"1190–1241","1192–1267":"1192–1267","1218–Male":"1218–Surnud","1170–1202":"1170–1202","1140–1202":"1140–1202","1190":"1190","about 1170":"umbes 1170","1230":"1230","1241":"1241","1140":"1140","1192":"1192","Dec 1202":"detsember 1202","Abt 1218":"umbes 1218","1170":"1170","1202":"1202","1267":"1267","1244":"1244","1218":"1218","Oxford, Oxfordshire, England":"Oxford, Oxfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Coggeshall, Oxfordshire, England":"Oxfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Coggs, Witney, Oxfordshire, England":"Witney, Oxfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Oxfordshire, England":"Oxfordshire, England","England":"